%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Energy-augmented CES Production Function (CESe)}
%------------------------------

Other energy economists use an energy-augmented Constant Elasticity of Substitution (CESe) production function to describe economic growth. The \texttt{R} \citep{R} package \texttt{micEconCES} \citep{Henningsen:2011td} estimates CES production functions of the form (among others)

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CESe}
  y = \gamma \: A \: \left\{\delta \left[\delta_1 k^{-\rho_1} + (1-\delta_1)l^{-\rho_1} \right]^{\rho/\rho_1} + (1-\delta) e^{-\rho} \right\}^{-1/\rho}; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent where the elasticity of substitution between capital ($k$) and labor ($l$) is given by $\sigma_1 = \frac{1}{1+\rho_1}$, the elasticity of substitution between ($kl$) and ($e$) is given by $\sigma = \frac{1}{1+\rho}$, $\delta$ describes the importance of ($kl$) relative to ($e$), and $\gamma$ is a fitting parameter, expected to be close to unity.

\citet{VanderWerf:2008tc} evalutes various nested CES production functions for 12 OECD countries with respect to climate change policy. \citeauthor{VanderWerf:2008tc} concludes that ($kl$)($e$) nesting structure best fits historical data. ******** Any confidence intervals in this study? ********* \citet{Lecca:2011kr} also evaluate a variety of CES production functions using a KLEM structure to determine how the various options for nesting the energy factor of production affect predictive ability. \citet{Stern:2012ey} also use a CES production function of the form ($kl$)($e$). \citeauthor{Stern:2012ey} apply their CES function to the Swedish economy from 1800-2000 and demonstrate the importance of the transition from wood to fossil fuels for economic growth.

%------------------------------
\subsubsection{LINEX Production Function}
%------------------------------

A third production function often cited in the literature is the LINear EXponential (LINEX) function \citep{Kummel:1980wx,Kummel:1982vy,Kummel:1985vz,Kummel:1989tf,Kummel:2002tx,Kummel:2010vz}:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:LINEX}
  y = Ae; A = \mathrm{e}^{a_0\left[2 \left(1 - \frac{1}{\rho_k} \right) + c_t \left(\rho_l - 1 \right)\right]},
\end{equation}

\noindent where $e$ is indexed energy and e is the base of the natural logarithm. The LINEX model assumes energy ($e$) is the only factor of production. $\rho_k \equiv \frac{k}{(1/2)(l+e)}$ and represents the rate at which capital stock increases relative to the average of labor and energy. $\rho_l \equiv \frac{l}{e}$ and represents the rate at which labor ($l$) increases relative to energy ($e$). Energy ($e$) as a factor of production is enhanced by $A$ if either

\begin{itemize}
\item{capital stock ($k$) increases faster than the average of energy ($e$) and labor ($l$), i.e. if $\rho_k >$ 1, or}
\item{labor ($l$) increases faster than energy ($e$), i.e. if $\rho_l >$ 1.}
\end{itemize}

\noindent According to the LINEX model, an economy that can increase capital stock ($k$) without a commensurate increase in labor ($l$) and energy ($e$) will experience an increase in output ($y$) in excess of its increase of energy consumption ($e$). Similarly, an economy benefits by increasing labor ($l$) without a commensurate increase in energy ($e$). Thus, $\rho_k$ is an efficiency of using labor and energy to make capital available to the economy, and $\rho_l$ is an efficiency of using energy to make labor available to the economy. The parameter $a_0$ represents the overall importance of these efficiencies, and $c_t$ represents the relative importance of the labor efficiency term compared to the capital stock efficiency term. In contrast to the Cobb-Douglas model (Equations \ref{eq:CD} and \ref{eq:CDe}) and the CES model (Equation \ref{eq:CESe}), the LINEX model (Equation \ref{eq:LINEX}) accounts for efficiencies directly and, therefore, does not employ a time-dependent technical progress term. \citet{Kummel:2002tx} use the LINEX production function to describe economic output for the economies of the U.S., Japan, and Germany. \citet{Warr:2010ga} compare the LINEX production function with the Cobb-Douglas production function to assess economic growth for Austria, the United Kingdom, the United States, and Japan. 

