%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Quantification of Energy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The literature shows three quantifications of energy ($e$) used in energy-augmented production functions: thermal energy ($q$), exergy ($x$), and useful work ($u$). Thermal energy ($q$) is the heat content of an energy carrier. Exergy ($x$) is the maximum useful work that can be extracted from an energy carrier by a process that brings the system into equilibrium with a heat reservoir (typically the surrounding environment). Useful work ($u$) includes the direct energy that goes into an economy, including work from machines, human muscles, and animals. Most energy economists have used thermal energy ($q$) for the energy factor of production ($e$) in energy-augmented production functions, including \citet{Stern:2012ey}, \citet{Froling:2009vo}, \citet{Serrenho:2010vq}, and \citet{Kummel:1980wx,Kummel:1982vy,Kummel:1985vz,Kummel:1989tf,Kummel:2002tx,Kummel:2010vz}. \citet{Warr:2010ga} introduced the idea of using exergy ($x$) and useful work ($u$) in a production function to account for efficiency gains in energy production and consumption over the last century. We know of no statistically-rigorous comparisons of the predictive ability of each type of energy quantification in the various types of production functions discussed in Section \ref{sec:Prod_Func_Forms}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economy Types}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In most energy-economic growth literature, economists assess developed economies from North America or Europe. Examples include \citet{Kummel:1980wx} applying LINEX to describe the West German economy, \citet{Serrenho:2010vq} applying Cobb-Douglas variants to EU-15 countries, \citet{VanderWerf:2008tc} applying CES nesting variants to the 12 OECD countries, \citet{Lecca:2011kr} applying CES nesting variants to the Scottish economy, \citet{Stern:2012ey} applying CES to describe the Swedish economy, and \citet{Warr:2012cg} using LINEX and Cobb-Douglas to describe the Austrian, American, British, and Japanese economies. 

In this paper, we evaluate example economies from four significant groups: Developed, BRICS, Petrol, and LDCs.\footnote{Lesser-Developed Countries} 

