%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Confidence Intervals for Cobb-Douglas and CES Models}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The key energy parameters for the Cobb-Douglas and CES models are $\gamma$, $\delta$, and $\sigma$. The parameter $\gamma$ in the Cobb-Douglas model (Equation \ref{eq:CD_With_Energy}) indicates the importance of energy for economic growth. When $\gamma \rightarrow 0$, energy is not a significant contributor to economic growth for an economy. Conversely, when $\gamma \rightarrow 1$, energy is the primary contributor to economic growth. However, if the 95\% confidence interval for $\gamma$ for any given economy extends to 0.0, we cannot say with high confidence whether or not energy makes a meaningful contribution to economic growth for that economy. On a graph of the width of the 95\% confidence interval for $\gamma$ ($CI_{95\%,\gamma}$) vs. $\gamma$, where each economy is represented by a point, the locus of points where the 95\% confidence interval on $\gamma$ crosses 0 is a diagonal line. If the combination of $\gamma$ and its confidence interval for a given economy is below and to the right of the line, we have high confidence that we can say whether or not energy is a significant contributor to economic growth. Thus, only when $\gamma$ is below the line and small (i.e., close to 0) for an economy, can we say with confidence that energy is an insignificant contributor to economic growth. Only when $\gamma$ is below the line and large (i.e., close to 1) for an economy can we say that energy is a significant contributor to economic growth, according to the Cobb-Douglas model.

The left column of graphs in Figure \ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} shows $CI_{95\%,\gamma}$ vs. $\gamma$ for the three quantifications of energy (thermal energy, $q$, exergy, $x$, and useful work, $u$). We note that most economies are above and to the left of the line, while only a few are below and to the right.

For the CES model (Equation \ref{eq:micEconCES_model}), the parameter $\delta$ indicates the importance of energy for economic growth. When $\delta \rightarrow 1$, energy is an insignificant contributor to economic growth, and when $\delta \rightarrow 0$, energy is the primary contributor to economic growth for an economy. However, if the 95\% confidence interval for $\delta$ extends to 1, we cannot say with high confidence whether or not energy makes a meaningful contribution to economic growth for that economy. In a manner similar to $\gamma$ for the Cobb-Douglas model, we note that if the combination of $\delta$ and its confidence interval for a given economy is below and to the left of the line, we have high confidence that we can say whether or not energy is a significant contributor to economic growth. Thus, only when $\delta$ is below the line and large (i.e., close to 1) for an economy, can we say with confidence that energy is an insignificant contributor to economic growth. Only when $\delta$ is below the line and small (i.e., close to 0) for an economy can we say that energy is a significant contributor to economic growth, according to the CES model.

The middle column of graphs in Figure \ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} shows $CI_{95\%,\delta}$ vs. $\delta$ for the three quantifications of energy (thermal energy, $q$, exergy, $x$, and useful work, $u$). We note that most economies are above and to the right of the line, while only a few are below and to the left.

For the CES model (Equation \ref{eq:micEconCES_model}), the parameter $\sigma$ indicates whether capital stock and labor ($kl$) and energy ($e$) are complements ($\sigma <$ 1) or substitutes ($\sigma >$ 1). For countries whose combination of  $\sigma$ and its confidence interval is below and to the left of the lines in the rightmost graphs of Figure \ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} we can say (with 95\% confidence) that ($kl$) and ($e$) are complements. For economies whose value of $\sigma$ is below and to the right of the line, we can say (with 95\% confidence) that ($kl$) and ($e$) are substitutes. For economies whose value of $\sigma$ is above those lines, we cannot say with 95\% confidence whether ($kl$) and ($e$) are substitues or complements.

The right column of graphs in Figure \ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} shows $CI_{95\%,\sigma}$ vs. $\sigma$ for the three quantifications of energy (thermal energy, $q$, exergy, $x$, and useful work, $u$). We note that energy ($e$) unambiguously complements capital stock and labor ($kl$) for most economies.

<<CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph, fig.width=ninePanelGraphWidth, fig.height=ninePanelGraphHeight, fig.pos="H", fig.cap="95\\% Confidence interval widths vs. parameter values for key energy parameters ($\\gamma$, $\\delta$, and $\\sigma$) of the Cobb-Douglas and CES models with energy. If an economy appears in the region above a dashed line, the 95\\% confidence interval for the parameter extends to or beyond $\\gamma \\le$ 0 (cannot say with 95\\% confidence that energy is important for the Cobb-Douglas model), $\\delta \\ge$ 1 (cannot say with 95\\% confidence that energy is important for the CES model), or $\\sigma$ = 1 (cannot say with 95\\% confidence whether ($kl$) and ($e$) are complements or substitutes in the CES model).">>=
CIvsParamLattice(countryAbbrevScaling=0.6)
@

Regardless of model (Cobb-Douglas or CES) or energy quantification ($q$, $x$, or $u$), there are few economies for which we can say with high confidence (at the 95\% level) that energy plays a significant role in economic growth. However, in seeming contradiction, results for the CES model indicate that energy complements capital stock and labor. That is, energy is essential for capital stock and labor to generate economic growth. One possible explanation for this apparent contradiction is to consider energy as embedded within capital stock and labor: it takes energy to make both captial stock and labor available to generate economic growth.

